to their everyday journeys. This book uses innovative quantitative and qualitative research methods to examine in depth, and in an international and historical context, why so many people fail to travel in ways that are deemed by most to be desirable. It proposes evidence-based policy solutions that could increase levels of walking and cycling substantially. This book is essential reading for planners and policy makers developing and implementing transport policies at both national and local levels, plus researchers and students in the field of mobility, transport, sustainability and urban planning.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aBicycle commutingxGovernment policyzGreat Britain. 0aUrban transportation policyzGreat Britain. 0aWalkingxGovernment policyzGreat Britain. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Regional Planning.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995z9783111196213oZDB-23-BUPP0 cprintz978144731008240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447310099423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447310099/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-BUPPc1995d2013